        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-02-28T06:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-02-28T06:00:00-05:00" n="93" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d93">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/2–2848: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Mukden</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ward</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mukden</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-02-28T19:00:00+08:00">February 28, 1948—7 p. m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 1—9:04 a. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>106. Yingkow captured by Communists February 26. Speed with which capture
                    executed indicates Government forces, consisting 1 division plus 2 regiments
                    former PPC<note n="80" xml:id="d93fn80">Peace Preservation Corps.</note> troops,
                    poorly equipped and trained and low morale caused by Government failure furnish
                    equipment <pb facs="0132" n="122" xml:id="pg_122"/> and ammunition although
                    having knowledge shortage since early summer, put up very little or no
                    resistance. Communist radio reports, probably accurate, state Wang Chia-shan, C.
                    O. Government’s 50th [<hi rend="italic">58th</hi>] Division of Fifty-second
                    Army, seized complete power Ying-kow and surrendered city together with 10,000
                    troops to Communists.</p>
                <p>Government leaders including Mayor Yuan Hung-ta and Cheng Ming-hsin, Chief Staff
                    who resisted surrender, were taken prisoner by Wang and troops desiring resist
                    Communists were disarmed.</p>
                <p>Sent Embassy, repeated Department 106, Tientsin 65, Peiping 75.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Ward</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
